## night shit employee workflow 

Here is a step-by-step walkthrough of how a Night Shift employee (e.g., working 10:00 PM to 6:00 AM) interacts with the system and how the data is processed.

1. The Check-In (Monday, 10:00 PM)
Action: The employee clicks "Check In" on Monday night.
System: A new AttendanceRecord is created with date = Monday and check_in_time = 22:00.
State: The employee is now "Checked In" and their dashboard shows an active session started on Monday.
2. The Midnight Break (Monday/Tuesday Transition)
Action: At 11:30 PM (Monday), the employee starts a break. At 12:30 AM (Tuesday), they end the break.
System: A BreakRecord is linked to Monday's attendance record.
Logic: Even though the break ended on Tuesday, the system sees that 12:30 AM is earlier than 11:30 PM. It realizes this crossed midnight and calculates the duration as 1 hour.
3. The Check-Out (Tuesday, 6:00 AM)
Action: The employee finishes their shift on Tuesday morning and clicks "Check Out".
System: Instead of looking for a "Tuesday" record (which doesn't exist yet), the system searches for any open session. It finds the one started on Monday.
Logic: It compares Monday 10:00 PM and Tuesday 6:00 AM. It detects the date rollover and calculates the total duration as 8 hours.
Calculation: Total Duration (8h) - Break (1h) = 7.00 Net Working Hours.
4. How it appears in Reports
Monthly Report: The entire 7.0 hours will appear under Monday's date.
Why? To keep reports predictable. If we split the shift, Tuesday would look like it has 6 hours of work with "no check-in," which would look like a bug. By anchoring the shift to the start date, the manager can see exactly which shift produced those hours.
Daily Dashboard: On Tuesday morning, the employee's dashboard will show they are "Checked Out." If they come back for their next night shift on Tuesday at 10:00 PM, they can check in again, and a fresh "Tuesday" record will begin.
5. Summary of Protection
Action	Traditional System	Your Hardened System
Check-Out	Crashes (Looking for today's record)	Success (Finds yesterday's open record)
Work Hours	Negative hours or 0.00	Success (Detects rollover +24h)
Break Time	Error in math	Success (Detects rollover +24h)
Next Shift	Blocks you (Already worked today)	Success (Separate records per start date)
This workflow ensures that even if your office operates 24/7, the attendance data remains accurate and the employees never get "stuck" in a session.

3:37 PM
